snippet.textDisplay:
As a progressive who supports the ERA, I can see both sides of this debate. On one hand, I feel that if you take the Supreme Court logic, each state that ratified the amendment would need to have since voted again and said no, we changed our minds, because otherwise the precedent should hold, one would think.

however, if this was on an amendment instead called the Bring Back Slavery Amendment, that was passed by 37 states in the 80's, and georgia today was just like, you know what, fuck it.... we'd all, Trevor included, instead be making the argument that you cannot pass a law that did 98% of the legislative work almost 40 years ago.

It's a tough decision. I think the correct decision is probably to simply have all the other 37 states (and the 12 who either didn't vote or voted no, I suppose) re-vote, because the Democrats in each state could probably make a great argument that if the legislative members of that state said yes 40 years ago, they should definitely vote yes now.


However, this is a question I think our society is quietly still trying to answer, and many people are disagreeing. Is what we are searching for true equality, as this amendment would give, or simply equity? Should women be on the front lines? Should men get the same amount of paternity leave as their wives, who actually had to undergo a procedure? I think a lot of people are quick to say fuck gender roles, including myself, but I've never met anyone who hasn't, even subconciously, re-enforced the different roles men and women play in every interaction from holding a door, paying for a date, or putting "you have to message ME first" in their tinder bio.

I'm not sure where people stand on this. I'm not even sure where I stand on it.
